onal Association of Wholesals\nDruggists of 'New York;, Isador\nStraus of New -York, and Theodore\nMarburg of Baltimore. All speak\ners were optimistic as to the finan\ncial and business outlook.\nMINERS CANNOT AGREE\nKANSAS CITY, April 10. Less\nhope prevailed today that an agree\nment would be reached between the\nminers' and the operators' joint con\nference.\nNational President T. L. Lewis of\nthe United Mine Workers of Amer\nilea, who was expected to come to\nKansas City in an effort to settle th?\ndifficulties, notified the miners that\nhis presence was needed in the east\nern fields, and he would be unabl\nto he here.\nIXDICTEII FOR PEONAGE\nGREENSBORO. N. C. April 10.\nThe grand Jury of the federal court\nnow In session here, returned true\nbills charging peonnRe against J. W.\nPrim of Mecklenbery county, a cot\nton mill man and agnlnst the follow\ning persons: D. S. Maddtuk. M. B.\nPower. J. 8. Harris. Joseph Tally\nand W. n. lUdellffo. Jain Flnle\nand John P. Elmore.\npquci mm\nFAILED\nTO MEET\nINTEREST\nBIG POWER COMPANY IS PLACEil\nIX HANDS OF RECEIVER\nAT NEW ORLEANS\nrl (By Associated Press.)\nNEW ORLEANS, La., April 10.\nThe Consumers' Electric company,\nwith a capital stock of bonds and oth\ner obligations aggregating about\n$2,500,000, was placed in a receiver\nship today, Samuel Insull, president\nof the Commonwealth Edison com\npany, Chicago, being pamed as re\nceiver. The receivership was asked\nfor by the National Conduit Cabls\ncompany of New York, holder ot $2.\n080,000 mortgage bonds of the com\npany. The petition for a receiver;\nship declared that the company had\ndefaulted in payment of interest due\non bonds, but the amount was .not\nstated. The Consumers' Electric com\npany (s one of two companies supply\ning lectrir light and power In New\nOrleans.\nTRUST COMPANY\nWANTS TO RESUME\nBy Ai9oclatearrfesiry' r\nNEW YORK, \"April j.0. The Wil\nliamsburg Trust company of Brook\nlyn, which went Into the hands of a\nreceiver October last, will resumo\nbusiness as soon as a plan ot reorgan\nization can be put into effect If the\ncourts permit. The receiver now has\non hand $1,300,000, which the di\nrectors hope to increase to $3,000.'\n000.\nMARKET BECAME\nQUITE ACTIVE\nNEW YORK, April 10. The stock\nmarket enjoyed a considerable per\niod of strength today,: but gave dur\ning the later stages of an advance\nof a reactionary tendency. The ad\nvances were especially sharp Jn a\nnumber of usually inactive stocks and\nrather erratic jumps, which weca\nforced In these, gave the market an\nartificial aspect which begot the spirit\nof caution in following the move\nments. The early strength in th3\nmarket was traceable to the Influ\nence of the Erie financial settlemenl\nstocks ot this company and Unl.m\nPacific leading the movement. Bonds\nwere firm.\nJAPANESE THINK\nVIE ARE MEDDLING\nTOKIO. April 10. The reported\nraid by Japanese on the native staT\nof the American consul general at\nMoukden cannot be confirmed In\nToklo. The Japanese papers are\nwondering why the Americans are\ninterfering on behalf of the Chinese,\nin spite of explicit treaty stipula\ntions providing for RuBso-Japanese\njurisdiction of the railway service 1 1\nManchuria. They express the hops\nthat the altruism of the American\nauthorities will not lead them to as\nslHt the Chinese In the recovery of\nImaginary rights.\nSAN FRANCISCO. Cal April 10.\nLEECH WIRES ACCEPTANCE j Twenty-three more veniremen\nMANILA, P. I.. April 10. John S.! were examined today In the Ford\nIh, public printer of the Philip- trial before Judge Lawlor. and of this\nplnea, who on April 4. was nominated number four' were passed aubject\nby president Roosevelt n public1 peremptory rhallengei. This Wt\nprinter to sucWed Charls Stilling.' nine men In the box when the case\nresigned, and today wired hi accept, wan adjourned until Monday morn\nnc ofrthe position. Mug..\nFight Promoter Disputes the\nRight of Constabulary to\nCollect Gambling Licehses.\nSpecial to The Bonanza\nRAWHIDE. Nev., April ID. A clash between the Btate po-\nlice and the authorities of Esmeralda county is imminent. An at-\ntempt on the part of the state\nlicenses from Tex Rlckard resulted in that person refusing to ad-'\nhere to the demands of the poll\nsave the sheriff's office in the matter of collecting gambling\nlicenses. District Attorney Swallow has wired to Rickard to stand\npat in the matter, as the police\nlaw and order only. If the police\nto Acting Governor Dickerson for\nusinessi Outlook Is\nGrowing Brighter\nNEW YORK, April lO.-rBrad-\nstreet's tomorrow will say; Though\nIrregular, week's, developments have\nbeen In the direction of improvement.\nThe approach of Easter has stimu\nlated the retail trade In some line.\nCollections show a slight gain. Busi\nness failures tor the week ending\nApril 9, number 258 against 247 last\nCanadian failures twenty-eight\nagainst thirty-two last week.\nJulia Mar love Deniss\nvonHernianit Charges\n(By Associated Press.)\nBOSTON, April 10. Julia Mar\nlowe wired an indignant denial to\nBoston from Montreal of the charges\ncontained in the divorce suit brought\nat Salem by Mrs. Clara Louise von\nHermann against Karl Stephen von\nHerrmann. She declares the charges\nare absurd and crazy.\nMaud Thorburn Backus, another\ncorespondent, denies any knowledge\nof the principals in the case. Evi\ndence that came out today point\nstrongly to collusion between von\nHerrmann and his wife in the case,\nand the Boston papers strongly hint\nat blackmail.1 i\n.The Journal says that von Herr\nmann offered them an \"exclusive ad\nvance story with inside facts\" to\ngether with pictures of himself and\nwife and highly sensational letters\nand photos of Julia Marlowe. He\nfirst wanted $500 and finally came\ndown to $10, and the Journal says\n\"He hawked the story all over\nnewspaper row in an endeavor to sell\nan article, which if true, as he guar\nanteed, would not only forever dis-\nSOUTHERN PACIFIC\nNEXT ON CARPET\n(By Associated Press.)\nLOS ANGELES, Cal., April 10.\nAfter devoting nearly- five days 'to\nInvestigating alleged violations of the\nstate lawd In granting Illegal rate\nby the Santa Ve and Salt Lake rail\nroads, the state railroad 1 commis\nsioners today adjourned to meet in\nSan Francisco, April 20, when an In\nqulry into the affairs ot the ficithem\nPacific will be resumed. The invea'\ntigation of the Santa Fe will again\nbe taken up in San Francisco, after\ndata now being complied in the rail\nroad's office is complete.\nNINE -MEN -TO TK FOKl:\nconstabulary to collect gambling\nje. He recognizes no authority\nare for the purpose of enforcing\narrest Rickard he will appeal\nrelief.'\nR, O. Dun Co'a. weekly review of\ntrade will say tomorrow: Commer\nclal conditions show little alteration,\nthe gains of the first quarter beinsr.\nmaintained, but further progress is\nextremely slow. Weather favored the\nretail trade in seasonable wearing ap\nparel at most points, and the outlook\nfor future business is brighter be\ncause of almost unanimous reports\nof satisfactory crop prospects.\ngrace himself and his wife, but a\ngreat American actress.\"\nThe Post says Mrs. von Herrmann\ndemanded pay for posing for her\nphotograph and referred them for\nmaterial to A. von Hargsteel at a\nBoston hotel, who proved to be von\nHerrmann himself. People who know\nthem well say the couple wre Hying\ntogether up to the filing of the suit.\nMISS MARLOWE PROSTRATED\nITHACA, N. Y., April 10. On re\nceiving the news in this city that she\nhad been named as a corespondent in\nthe suit for divorce brougTit by Mrs.\nClara Louise von Hermann against\nKarl Stephens von Herrmann, Misi\nJulia Marlowe, the actress, was ove -come\nand hadto cancel her engage\nment in \"Gloria at the Lyceum the\natre here.\nMiss Marlowe arrived in a private\ncar from Canada. Her car was be\nsieged by newspapermen, but she\nwould not be seen and referred the\nreporters to her manager, who de\nclared he had nothing to say in ref\nerence to the matter.\nDISCHARGED FOR\nPOLITICAL ACTIVITY\nAssociated Press.)\nWASHINGTON, D. C, Ap-11 10.\nThe second case of suspension of a\ncivil service employe for political ac-\ntivity occurred today, when Acting\nPrinter Brian, on the recommenda\ntlon of the civil service commission.\nsuspended William Koll, an employe\nof the bindery of the government\nprinting office, for alleged pernlclou\npolitical activity. B. H. Warner, Re-I\npublican candidate for congress In\nthe sixth district. Maryland, charge'\nthat Koll served as chairman of tho\npolitical meetings In the Interests\nan opponent of Warner,\nTWO MORE Jl'ROKS\n(By Associated Press.)\nSAN FRANCISCO. Cal.. April 10.\nTwo more veniremen were quali\nfied to try Ab Roef In the Farksld\nbribery rase today, making six ju\nora tvinioirily wed subjct tq\nperemptory challenge.\nWilis\nEMINENT PHYSICIAN CALLED IN\nCONSULTATION IN AD\nMIRAL'S CASE\n(By Associated Press)\nlos\nANGELES, Cal., Dr.\nWilliam A. Edwards of this\ncity, brother-in-law of Secre-\ntary Taft, has been summoned\nto Paso Robles to attend a con-\nsulfation with Surgeon McDon-\naid, who is attending Admiral\nEvans, Edwards leaves tomor-\nrow morning by special train\nfor the hot, springs.\nBARTNETT SECURES\nRELEASE ON BAIL\n(,By Associated Press.)\nSAN FRANCESCO, Cal., April\" 10\nWalter J. Baftnett, one of the di\nrectors of the defunct California. Safe\nDeposit and Trust company, was re\nleased from custody tonight after be\ning in jail for four months.. There\nare three charges against him, one\nfor. embezzling the Colton securities\nand bonds of the Sacramento Valley\nbank and stealing notea worth $30,\n000. Bartnett was released after put\nting up $250,000 bonds.\nWAVES THREATEN\nPASSEfMR TRAIN\nOGDEN, Utah, April 10y The pas\nsenger trains from the east did noi\narrive until 7:15 this morning. The\ndelay was caused by a heavy storm,\nraging on Great Salt Lake and it\nwas deemed unsafe for trains to cross\nover the Lucin cut-off nntil the storm\nsubsided somewhat. Passengers on\nthe late trains stated that the wav\nwere so high on the lake that the cars\nwould have been In danger of being\nswept from the trestle had the trains\nbeen sent across the cut-off when, the\nstorm was at its height..\nSUICIDE DEFENSE\nIN MURDER TRIAL\n(By Associated Press)\nOAKLAND, Cal., April 10. The\nactual trial of Mark A. Wllklns, In\ndicted for the murder of Vernle Car\nmin, was commenced in Judge Mel\nvln's court, and the lines on which\nthe prosecution and defense wilt be\nLconducted were made clear for the\nfirst time. The prosecution, will try\nto show that Wllklns murdered the\nwoman with robbery as a motive, and\nthe defense-will try to show that she\ncommitted suicide to avoid the ehame\nof the exposure of her relations with\nWilkins. f\"\nThe tactics were outlined in the\nopening speech to the jury by Dis\ntrict Attorney Brown, which was fol\nlowed by an address by Attorney\nHugh Mclsaac for Wllklns. The pro\nceeding was unusual, but Judge Mel-\nvir ruled that because considerable\nnf the testimony to be given against\nWilkltis would be construed by his\nside in an entirely different light It\nwould he only fair to direct the\nJury's attention to the necessity o\nlooking at the testimony and evidence\nfrom both sides from th very be\nginning of the case.\nKEFUSKD TO LOWER BAIL j\n(By Associated Press)\n8 AN. FRANCISCO. Cal.. April 1.\nao application 10 rresiamg juas;\nJ... A in in- I\nJohnson to have the ball of J. Di.\nrell Brown, the Indicted banker, re\nduced from $320,000 to $100,000 was\nd.sled by th Judfje on the grouil\nthat be has no jurisdiction, the In\ndlctmenti having bea awltipd to\nJ J idge Dunne's court.\nINHABITANTS OF TWO MEXICAi\nTILLAGES FLEE FROM I\nTHEIR HOMES I\n(By Associated Press.)\nMONTEREY, Mex.. April 10.-Te\neg rams from Alter and Noriega sat\nthat several distinct earthquake.\nshocks were felt in those neighbor i\nhoods Wednesday, followed by shock1\nyesterday. Owing to the severe na\nture of the quakes, which were wors\nthan any ever experienced there be?\nfore, great alarm was felt \"by resii\ndents, many of whom are said to hav\nf1wi tmm thatf hnmog tn nth or tnwnf\nJURY FAILS TO\nREACH VERDICT\nHELENA, Mont., April 10. Attej\nbeing out more than twenty-elghj\nnours, tne jury in me joint case oij\nOliver Dallas and the chief clerk ir\nthe federal surveyor, general's office\nfailed to agree and were discharge\ntonight by Judge William Hunt Thf\nmen were tried on a charge of con\nspiracy to defraud the government,\ngrowing out of alleged fraudulent\nsurveys. The case against Alber\nHo'vey, who was Indicted on the aam\nago upon his turning state's evidence.\nFORTUNE HUNTER\nF0HBED A UIIU\n(By Associated Press.)\nSCRANTON, Pa.. April 10. J\nGeorge B. Schooley of Philadephla.\nclaimant for the fortune ot James\nW. Crawford, his cousin, a million-\naire coal operator of this city who\ndied three years ago in Florida,\npleaded guilty here to the forgery of\nthe Bccalled Schooley will, under\nwhich he, was to Inherit practically\nall the Crawfordfortune.\nCharles R. Eldel and Albert Ban-\nman, the other confederates In the\ncase are- awaiting sentence.\nMONEYCHANGERS\nSUPPORT BOYCOTT\n(By Associated Press.)\nHONGKONG, April 10. Chinese\nmoney changers here are supporting\nthe boycott against the Japanese,\nwhich came into existence as the re\nsult of the Tatsu Maru incident, by\nrefusing to accept Japanese bank\nnotes even at a discount.\nILL PROVIDES F\nNEW MINE BUREAU\nW ASHINGTON, D. C, April 10.\nThe house committee on mines an I\nmining will make a favorable report\nestablishment of a bureau of mine?.\nThe subcommittee in charge of the\nbill already has given it favorabl?\nconsideration. All the details ot tho\nmessage have not yet feaen\"settled,\nbut It la probable the proposed bureau\n,win be placed Nmder the jurisdic\ntion of the interior department.\nMining, interests, and mine em\nployes all over the country are; tn\nfavor ot such a bureau. Some bav\ngone so far as to advocate- a depart\nment of mines and mining.\nI'AUFOKMW-.HKVAbA A.-\nH;-\nSANTA ANA. Cal.. April 10. At\ntoday's session ot the Calltoriila-X-'-vada\nemamnnient of G. A. R. offic -m\nwere elected and delegate to the na\ntional encampment were seWtt.!\nPatiidena was asrevj up\" f- Vl\"\nplar for boldin th xt viu&u. i\nwent. 8. MerrtH of Iadx Ueai h.\nrl-s teit ,unilud'r-ln-rht'f.","height":"26556","width":"18176"}}
